Below is a **complete, self‑contained example** that shows how you can expose BlockSci’s C++ block iterator to Python in a way that feels natural to Python users (just like `pandas.DataFrame.apply` or `polars.lazy.map`).  

The code is written with **pybind11** (the de‑facto standard for C++ ↔ Python bindings) and contains:

* a tiny mock‑up of the BlockSci C++ API (`Block`, `BlockIterator`, `BlockChain`);
* the pybind11 wrapper that implements the Python‑facing API;
* a short “usage” section that you can paste into a Python REPL or notebook to see how it works.

> **TL;DR** – The public Python API is:
> ```python
> chain = BlockChain(path_to_blocks)          # create a view over the chain
> for block in chain:                         # normal Python iteration
>     print(block.height, block.hash)
>
> # “hot‑path” – call a user‑function for every block (or for batches of blocks)
> chain.foreach(my_func)                      # one block at a time
> chain.foreach(my_batch_func, batch_size=1024)   # batches for extra speed
> ```

---

## 1.  The C++ side (mocked BlockSci)

```cpp
// blockscipy.cpp
// ------------------------------------------------------------
// Compile with:  c++ -O3 -Wall -shared -std=c++17 -fPIC \
//                $(python3 -m pybind11 --includes) blockscipy.cpp \
//                -o blockscipy$(python3-config --extension-suffix)
// ------------------------------------------------------------

#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/stl.h>          // for std::vector conversion
#include <pybind11/functional.h>   // for passing std::function / py::function
#include <cstdint>
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <memory>
#include <stdexcept>

namespace py = pybind11;

/* ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Mock‑up of the real BlockSci C++ API.
   In production you would #include the real headers instead of these.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------*/

struct Block {
    uint64_t height;          // block height (0‑based)
    std::string hash;         // hex string, 64 chars
    uint32_t   tx_count;      // number of transactions in the block
    // … many other fields …

    // A tiny constructor for the mock data set.
    Block(uint64_t h, const std::string& hsh, uint32_t tx)
        : height(h), hash(hsh), tx_count(tx) {}
};

/* A very simple iterator that pretends to walk 800 million blocks.
   The real BlockIterator would be a thin wrapper around BlockSci’s
   internal iterator that yields a `Block` view on each step. */
class BlockIterator {
public:
    explicit BlockIterator(uint64_t start = 0, uint64_t end = 800'000'000ULL)
        : cur_(start), end_(end) {}

    // Return true if there is another block.
    bool has_next() const { return cur_ < end_; }

    // Return the next block (by value – cheap because Block is POD‑like).
    Block next() {
        if (!has_next())
            throw std::out_of_range("BlockIterator exhausted");
        // In the real implementation this would pull data from the
        // blockchain files.  Here we fabricate deterministic data.
        std::string hash = "0000000000000000000" + std::to_string(cur_);
        uint32_t tx = static_cast<uint32_t>((cur_ % 1000) + 1);
        Block blk(cur_, hash, tx);
        ++cur_;
        return blk;
    }

private:
    uint64_t cur_;
    uint64_t end_;
};

/* The high‑level entry point that users create from Python. */
class BlockChain {
public:
    explicit BlockChain(const std::string& path_to_blocks)
        : path_(path_to_blocks), iter_(0, mock_block_count()) {}

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // Python iteration protocol (for … in chain)
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    BlockIterator begin() const { return iter_; }   // used only for pybind11
    BlockIterator end()   const { return BlockIterator(mock_block_count(), mock_block_count()); }

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // The hot‑path: call a Python callable for each block (or each batch)
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    void foreach(py::function py_func, size_t batch_size = 1) const {
        if (batch_size == 0)
            throw std::invalid_argument("batch_size must be >= 1");

        // We *release* the GIL while we walk the C++ iterator.
        // The GIL is reacquired only when we need to call the Python function.
        py::gil_scoped_release release;

        if (batch_size == 1) {
            // One‑by‑one mode – the cheapest for the user because they get a
            // single Block object each time.
            while (iter_.has_next()) {
                Block blk = iter_.next();
                // Re‑acquire GIL just for the call.
                py::gil_scoped_acquire acquire;
                py_func(blk);
                // GIL is released again when the loop iterates.
            }
        } else {
            // Batch mode – we accumulate a std::vector<Block> and hand the
            // whole batch to Python as a list of Block objects.
            std::vector<Block> batch;
            batch.reserve(batch_size);

            while (iter_.has_next()) {
                batch.push_back(iter_.next());
                if (batch.size() == batch_size) {
                    py::gil_scoped_acquire acquire;
                    py_func(batch);          // pybind11 automatically converts
                    batch.clear();
                }
            }
            // Send the final, possibly‑partial batch.
            if (!batch.empty()) {
                py::gil_scoped_acquire acquire;
                py_func(batch);
            }
        }
    }

private:
    std::string path_;                 // just stored for completeness
    BlockIterator iter_;               // iterator over the whole chain

    // In a real build this would query the blockchain files for the exact count.
    static uint64_t mock_block_count() { return 800'000'000ULL; }
};

/* ------------------------------------------------------------------
   pybind11 binding code – this is the only thing the Python user sees.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------*/

PYBIND11_MODULE(blockscipy, m) {
    m.doc() = "Python bindings for a (mock) BlockSci block iterator";

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // Expose the Block struct – read‑only attributes.
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    py::class_<Block>(m, "Block")
        .def_property_readonly("height",   [](const Block& b){ return b.height; })
        .def_property_readonly("hash",     [](const Block& b){ return b.hash; })
        .def_property_readonly("tx_count", [](const Block& b){ return b.tx_count; })
        .def("__repr__", [](const Block& b) {
            return "<Block height=" + std::to_string(b.height) +
                   " hash='" + b.hash.substr(0, 12) + "...' txs=" +
                   std::to_string(b.tx_count) + ">";
        });

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // Expose the BlockChain class.
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    py::class_<BlockChain>(m, "BlockChain")
        .def(py::init<const std::string&>(),
             py::arg("path_to_blocks"),
             "Create a view over a BlockSci data directory.")
        // Python iteration protocol – enables: `for blk in chain: ...`
        .def("__iter__", [](const BlockChain& self) {
            // The iterator object we return is a *copy* of the underlying
            // BlockIterator, so `iter_` stays at the start for each new loop.
            return py::make_iterator(self.begin(), self.end());
        }, py::keep_alive<0, 1>())   // keep BlockChain alive while iterator lives
        // The hot‑path: call a Python callable for each block (or for batches)
        .def("foreach",
             &BlockChain::foreach,
             py::arg("func"),
             py::arg("batch_size") = 1,
             R"pbdoc(
                Walk the entire chain and invoke ``func`` for each block.

                Parameters
                ----------
                func : Callable[[Block] | Callable[[List[Block]]], None]
                    A Python callable that receives either a single ``Block`` (if
                    ``batch_size`` is 1) or a list of ``Block`` objects (if
                    ``batch_size`` > 1).

                batch_size : int, optional
                    Number of blocks to accumulate before invoking ``func``.
                    ``1`` (default) gives a per‑block callback; larger values
                    reduce the number of Python calls at the cost of extra
                    memory.  Typical values are ``256``‑``4096``.

                Notes
                -----
                The GIL is released while scanning the chain, and reacquired only
                when calling ``func``.  This makes the loop essentially as fast as
                a pure‑C++ walk, with the overhead of a single Python call per
                batch.
            )pbdoc")
        ;
}
```

### How to compile

```bash
c++ -O3 -Wall -shared -std=c++17 -fPIC \
    $(python3 -m pybind11 --includes) blockscipy.cpp \
    -o blockscipy$(python3-config --extension-suffix)
```

*The command works on Linux/macOS with a recent compiler and a Python ≥ 3.8.
On Windows you can use the same flags with MSVC (or just let `scikit‑build`
handle it).*

---

## 2.  Python‑side usage (what the end‑user sees)

```python
# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Example usage – paste into a fresh Python interpreter or notebook
# --------------------------------------------------------------
import blockscipy as bs

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1️⃣  Normal Python iteration (just like any other container)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
chain = bs.BlockChain("/path/to/blocks")   # path is ignored in the mock

print("First 5 blocks:")
for blk in chain:                         # uses the __iter__ implementation
    print(blk.height, blk.hash[:12] + "...", blk.tx_count)
    if blk.height >= 4:
        break

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# 2️⃣  Per‑block callback – the hot path
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
def my_per_block(blk: bs.Block):
    # Imagine a heavy computation that needs the block's hash & height.
    # Keeping the function tiny makes the benchmark realistic.
    if blk.height % 10_000_000 == 0:
        print(f"[{blk.height}] hash starts with {blk.hash[:8]}")

# This will walk *all* ~800 M blocks, calling `my_per_block` for each.
# In a real run you would probably stop early or filter inside the loop.
# For the demo we only walk the first 30 M blocks (feel free to adjust).
chain.foreach(my_per_block)          # batch_size defaults to 1 (per‑block)

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# 3️⃣  Batch callback – much faster when the user can work on vectors.
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
def my_batch(batch):
    # `batch` is a list of Block objects.
    # Example: compute the total number of transactions in the batch.
    total_txs = sum(b.tx_count for b in batch)
    # Print only occasionally, to avoid flooding stdout.
    if batch[0].height % 5_000_000 == 0:
        print(f"[{batch[0].height}] batch of {len(batch)} blocks → {total_txs} txs")

# Process blocks in batches of 4096 – only 800 M/4096 ≈ 195 k Python calls!
chain.foreach(my_batch, batch_size=4096)
```

### What the user gets

* **Familiar Pythonic feel** – `for blk in chain:` works exactly like any iterable.
* **Maximum performance** – the heavy lifting (reading the block files, advancing the iterator) stays in C++; the GIL is released for the whole walk and only taken back when invoking the user callback.
* **Flexibility** – the callback can work on a single `Block` (the default) or on a *batch* of blocks, which mirrors the `apply`/`map` APIs of `pandas` and `polars`.
* **Zero‑copy semantics** – `Block` is a lightweight POD object; pybind11 copies it into a Python object only when the callback is called. No extra memory churn for the 800 M‑element walk.

---

## 3.  Why this design works for the hot path

| Concern | Solution in the binding |
|---------|--------------------------|
| **GIL contention** | `py::gil_scoped_release` releases the interpreter lock while the C++ loop runs; the lock is reacquired only for the user‑provided Python call. |
| **Per‑call overhead** | The loop is pure C++ until the callback; each call costs only the normal pybind11 conversion (≈ 200 ns for a tiny struct). |
| **User‑level vectorisation** | The optional `batch_size` lets users amortise the Python‑call cost over many blocks (same idea as `DataFrame.apply(..., chunk_size=…)`). |
| **Safety & lifetime** | `py::keep_alive<0,1>()` on the iterator ensures the `BlockChain` object stays alive while a Python iterator is in use. |
| **Ease of use** | The API mirrors familiar data‑frame patterns, so data‑scientists can drop it into existing scripts with no extra boilerplate. |

---

### TL;DR – The public API you can ship

```python
# blockscipy/__init__.py   (just re‑export the compiled module)
from ._blockscipy import Block, BlockChain   # the pybind11 module is named _blockscipy
```

```python
# ---- user code -------------------------------------------------
from blockscipy import BlockChain

chain = BlockChain("/path/to/blocks")

# 1️⃣ Normal iteration
for blk in chain:
    print(blk.height, blk.hash)

# 2️⃣ Per‑block callback (fastest possible)
def process_one(blk):
    # heavy work …
    pass
chain.foreach(process_one)          # batch_size defaults to 1

# 3️⃣ Batch callback (still fast, lower Python‑call overhead)
def process_batch(batch):
    # batch is a list[Block]
    …
chain.foreach(process_batch, batch_size=2048)
```

That’s it – a clean, Pythonic, high‑performance binding that lets users inject their own per‑block logic without paying the cost of a Python‑level loop over 800 million items. Happy hacking!
